        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Vineland, New Jersey,</placeName>
                    <date>Oct. 22, 1874.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Darwin,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>My observations on <hi rend="underline">Dionaea</hi> are now completed and ready for publication. I am afraid I have delayed too long in giving you the desired information with regard to the leaf catching more than one insect.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>Several leaves caught successively, three insects each, but most of them were not able to digest the third fly; but died in the attempt.</p>
<p>Five leaves digested, each three flies, and closed over the fourth, but died soon after the fourth capture.</p>
<p>Many leaves did not digest even one large insect.</p>
<p>I will try to send you my observations when published.</p>
<p>Respectfully yours | Mary Treat.</p>
<p>I read Dr Hooker’s admirable address on “Carnivorous Plants”, in <hi rend="underline">Nature</hi> with much interest.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="annotations">
                <note>2.1 Several … attempt. 2.2] <hi rend="italic">scored red crayon</hi></note>
                <note>3.1 digested] ‘however,’ <hi rend="italic">interl after ink</hi></note>
                <note>3.2 capture] ‘was’ <hi rend="italic">interl after ink</hi></note>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9505.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Mary Treat, 22 June 1874</ref>. CD quoted this information from Treat in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref>, p. 311. Treat did not publish on <hi rend="italic">Dionaea</hi> (Venus fly trap), but she had previously sent observations to CD in her letter of 8 June 1874.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">J. D. Hooker 1874b.</note>
        </div>        
            
